{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between request-construction logic and the API client payload. A unit test of only a helper can miss dropped fields during module wiring/serialization. Higher levels are not required: behavior text is only about request contents (\"includes the complete list\"), not real network/OS effects or model judgment.","test_description":"Wire the classifier with a stub transport/client that records outbound payload. Call classify with a taxonomy and assert the sent request contains every label exactly as configured.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core failure is deterministic mapping/validation logic on returned label membership. No real infra or model-quality dependence is needed; a fake response with an out-of-taxonomy label reproduces the bug. Integration was considered but rejected because behavior text targets normalization outcome, not cross-module state propagation.","test_description":"Test normalization/classification decision function (or object boundary with mocked API result) using an invalid label and assert output is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure determinism/idempotence of normalization given identical input. A local function/object test catches real failures (state leakage, nondeterministic parsing). Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: it explicitly scopes to \"identical raw API responses\" and \"normalization step,\" not live provider behavior.","test_description":"Invoke normalization repeatedly with the same raw response fixture and taxonomy; assert the final label is identical across runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.93,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on repeated live model calls and label stability from real AI output. Mocking would hide true model variability. Workflow was considered and rejected because this is repeated single-step classification, not multiple distinct agentic stages chained with handoff.","test_description":"Run N repeated real classification calls for the same input, record provider raw responses and final labels, and assert label changes only occur when provider response content changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at module boundary: config + token-budget enforcement + dispatch gating. A pure unit on truncation logic can miss bugs where over-budget requests are still dispatched. System/Agentic rejected: behavior says \"before dispatch\" and focuses on local enforcement policy, not real provider/model output.","test_description":"Instantiate classifier with real request-builder and budget policy, plus stub API client. Feed over-budget documents and assert configured truncate/reject behavior and that dispatch occurs or is blocked accordingly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires real provider-reported usage from a real AI API call; stubs can always return compliant usage and hide tokenizer/accounting mismatches. System was considered but rejected as final because the decisive risk is AI-provider behavior/metadata from the real model endpoint, which falls under agentic dependency.","test_description":"Execute real calls with representative documents, capture provider token-usage metadata, and assert observed usage is <= configured budget with margin policy if defined.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0.67,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry orchestration across modules (API client error -> backoff/wait -> retry -> return). In-process stubs and fake timers can reproduce the real failure without OS/network. Higher levels rejected: behavior is about control flow on 429/rate-limit signal, not model output quality or multi-agent sequence.","test_description":"Use a stub client that returns rate-limit error then success; run classifier with controlled clock/backoff and assert it waits, retries expected times, and returns success instead of surfacing the first error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":nu